Background¶

This homework assignment focuses on data from the World Happiness Report.

The World Happiness Report is a landmark survey of the state of global happiness. The first report was published in 2012, the second in 2013, the third in 2015, and the fourth in the 2016 Update. The World Happiness 2017, which ranks 155 countries by their happiness levels, was released at the United Nations at an event celebrating International Day of Happiness on March 20th. The report continues to gain global recognition as governments, organizations and civil society increasingly use happiness indicators to inform their policy-making decisions. Leading experts across fields economics, psychology, survey analysis, national statistics, health, public policy and more describe how measurements of well-being can be used effectively to assess the progress of nations. The reports review the state of happiness in the world today and show how the new science of happiness explains personal and national variations in happiness.

We will be using data from the 2016 report.

Your main task in this assignment is to explore the data using the data manipulation, analysis, visualization, and applied statistical methods we covered in class as well as those in the assigned readings.

4) Finally, create JointGrid Visualizations that show the p-value and personr score for all the different relationships:¶

  2. Happiness vs. Economy
  3. Happiness vs. Health

In [16]:
for column in subset.columns: 
    if column != "Happiness Score": 
        g2 = sns.JointGrid(data=subset,x='Happiness Score',y=column)
        g2.plot(sns.regplot, sns.distplot)
        g2.annotate(stats.pearsonr)
        g2.fig.subplots_adjust(top=0.9)
        g2.fig.suptitle("Happiness Score Versus {}".format(column), fontsize=12)

Explanation:¶

The Pearson correlation coefficient (located in the top right of each visualization) measures the linear relationship between two datasets. The calculation of the p-value relies on the assumption that each dataset is normally distributed. According to https://docs.scipy.org/doc/scipy/reference/generated/scipy.stats.pearsonr.html, "Like other correlation coefficients, this one varies between -1 and +1 with 0 implying no correlation. Correlations of -1 or +1 imply an exact linear relationship. Positive correlations imply that as x increases, so does y. Negative correlations imply that as x increases, y decreases. The p-value roughly indicates the probability of an uncorrelated system producing datasets that have a Pearson correlation at least as extreme as the one computed from these datasets."

1. Happiness vs. Family

Happiness Sore and Family have a correlation. This is because as happiness score increases so does Family. The personr value calculated shows if the two variables have a correlation. The personr for Happiness Score versus Family is 0.74, indicating that there is a strong linear relationship/correlation present. The p-value of 2.1e-28 is less than 0.05. This means that this is a statistically significant model, and we can reject the null hypothesis.

2. Happiness vs. Economy

Happiness Sore and Economy have a correlation. This is because it appears that as happiness score increases so does Economy (GDP per Capita). The personr for Happiness Score versus Economy is 0.79, indicating that there is a strong linear relationship present. The p-value of 8.5-35 is less than 0.05. This means that this is a statistically significant model, and we can reject the null hypothesis.

3. Happiness vs. Health

Happiness Sore and Health appear to have a correlation. This is because it appears that as happiness score increases so does Health. The personr for Happiness Score versus Health is 0.77, indicating that there is a strong linear relationship present. The p-value of 1.8-35 is less than 0.05. This means that this is a statistically significant model, and we can reject the null hypothesis.

4. Happiness vs. Freedom

Happiness Sore and Freedom appear to have a correlation. This is because it appears that as happiness score increases so does Freedom. The personr for Happiness Score versus Freedom is 0.57, indicating that there is a moderate linear relationship present/correlation. The p-value of 1e-14 is less than 0.05. This means that this is a statistically significant model, and we can reject the null hypothesis.

5. Happiness vs. Trust

Happiness Sore and Trust (Government Corruption) do not have a correlation. The personr for Happiness Score versus Trust(Government Corruption) is 0.4, indicating that there is a moderate correlation/linear relationship present. The p-value of 1.8e-07 is less than 0.05. This means that this is a statistically significant model, and we can reject the null hypothesis.

6. Happiness vs. Generosity

Happiness Sore and generoisty have a very weak correlation. The personr for Happiness Score versus Generosity is 0.16, indicating that there is a very weak linear relationship/correlation present. The p-value of 0.05 is not less than 0.05. This means that this is not a statistically significant model, and we do not reject the null hyopothesis.

1) Add a column called quartile to the happiness DataFrame, and assigned each row to a quartile based on their happiness rank.¶

In [18]:
quartile = len(happiness)//4
happiness["Quartile"] = happiness["Happiness Rank"]
happiness["Quartile"].iloc[:quartile] = 1 

second_quartile = quartile + quartile
happiness["Quartile"].iloc[quartile:second_quartile] = 2

third_quartile = second_quartile + quartile
happiness["Quartile"].iloc[second_quartile:third_quartile ]= 3 
happiness["Quartile"].iloc[third_quartile:] = 4

Explanation:¶

In the above code I assigned each row to a quartile based in their happiness rank. The last quartile, quartile 4, has more rows than the other groups. Quartile 4 has 40 rows and the rest of the quartiles have 39. This is shown in the code below:

3) create a mosiac plot of region and quartile to help understand the interaction between region and happiness quartile¶

In [21]:
dic_colors = {1: "r", 2: "b",3: "g", 4: "y"}
props = lambda key: {'color': dic_colors[int(key[1])]}

with plt.rc_context():
    plt.rc("figure", figsize=(18,12))
    mosaic(happiness, ['region','quartile'],
           properties = props,
           title = "Region and Happiness Quartile",
           labelizer = lambda k: " ", #k[1], #this is makes it so labels are blank 
           #gap=0.0005,
           label_rotation = 90
          )
    legenditems = [(plt.Rectangle((0,0),1,1, color=dic_colors[c]), "%s" %c)
                 for i,c in enumerate(happiness['quartile'].unique().tolist())]
    plt.legend(*zip(*legenditems))
Explanation:¶

There appears to be an effect of region on happiness quartile. The mosiac is jagged which indicates that there is an effect on the variable tested and the measure. Sub-Saharan Africa is most likely to be in quartile 4, and North America and Australia and New Zealand are more likely to be in the 1st quartile. If there was no effect of region on happiness quartile the mosiac would not be jagged.

Explanation:¶

The chi-squared value explains the difference that exists between the observed counts and the counts expected if there is no relationship in the population being viewed. The output table contains the expected values, which look a lot different than the observed values in the contigency table(which is called ct made in part 4 above).

The chi-squared statistic is 139.6164992152685 which is very big. The associated probability is way less than 0.05. The probability of getting this by chance is very small, as the p-value is 3.823562988526965e-17. This means that this is a statistically significant model because the p-value is less than 0.05. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis of no interaction, and say that there is an interaction effect between happeiness score and quartile. As well, this suggests that happiness quartile and region are not independent. This result is consistant with the mosiac plot created above. This further proves that there seems to be an interaction between happiness quartile and region.

Explanation:¶

The R-squared vaule is how much of overall variance is explained by linear expression/model. 54.6 percent of overall variance is explained by this model. However, the p-value, called "Prob (F-statistic)" in the output is 2.09e-28 which is less than 0.05. This means that this is a statistically significant model, and we can reject the null hypothesis, because the probability of getting the F-Statistic by chance is less than 0.05.

The P>|t| means that the coeffcients for the model are statistically significant. If this value is smaller than 0.05, than the model is statistically significant. Here both coefficents are smaller than 0.05( both are 0.000); Therefore, you can formulate a regression equation from these coeffcients.

Since the estimates for the parameters of the model are statistically significant, we can use the equation Happiness Score = 3.1645 * Family + 2.8708 to predict the value of Happiness Score given a value for Family.

Determining the influence from an outlier is difficult to do for every single point. As you can see, the index value of 74 has a large negative residual, and the point does not appear to have significant leverage. The index value of 74 is not referring to the country Mongolia. I am going to look at the cook's distance values to further investigate the influence of Mongolia, but from the influence plot it does not appear to have a significant influence on the regression because it is not labeled.

Explanation:¶

I reset the index of eastern_asia_countries so that the index of each row would match up to df (the DataFrame with the columns cooks_distance and pvalue). I assigned this DataFrame to the variable new. After this I found the row that is equal to Mongolia by filtering the DataFrame new, where the index column is equal to index_of_country_with_lowest_happiness_score (Mongolia's index). I then found the new index of Mongolia, which will be the same/correspond directly to the index in df. I assigned this index to the variable corresponding_index_in_df. I used iloc and corresponding_index_in_df to find the row that has Mongolia's cooks_distance and pvalue in df.

Another way to get Mongolia's cooks_distance and pvalue from df is to do df.set_index(eastern_asia_countries["Country"]). I assigned this new DataFrame to the variable country_as_index and used .loc to get the row whose index is the same as the string name_of_country (name_of_country is a string with name of the country with the lowest happiness score).

I found that Mongolia has a pvalue of 0.743465 and the cooks distance is 0.319529. This is consistant with the cooks distance I found in the DataFrame sm_fr for Mongolia. Again, Mongolia's Cook's distance measure of 0.319529 shows that this observation does not have much influence on the regression results because it is not greater than 1.
